PLOTS OBSERVATIONS — PHASE 2 (live data)
========================================
Notes for each plot in 03_live_data_visualization.ipynb.
Each entry: what the plot shows, what it means, and any modeling implication.


1. sns.histplot price  --  Price distribution across all offers
---------------------------------------------------------------
- Distribution is clearly BIMODAL, not just right-skewed: primary peak
  around $300 with ~2200 offers, secondary hump around $800-900 with
  ~500 offers, long tail to $2400.
- Two modes likely correspond to two market segments — short-haul
  domestic ($200-400) and long-haul international ($700-1000).
- Modeling implication: a single linear model will split the
  difference between the two modes and fit neither well. Tree models
  (XGBoost / LightGBM) will pick up the regime split automatically via
  is_international / distance features.


2. sns.scatterplot price vs lead_time_days  --  Price vs lead time
------------------------------------------------------------------
- L-shaped scatter: dense band 0-100 days at prices $100-1000, sparser
  cloud beyond 100 days.
- NO obvious price-vs-lead-time slope — prices look similar whether
  booked 5 days out or 80. Counterintuitive vs the "book early =
  cheaper" assumption.
- Vertical wall at ~200 days is the 7-month query horizon — script
  doesn't query further out, so density drops to zero. Artifact, not
  signal.
- Modeling implication: lead time matters within a route, not across
  them. Need to facet by distance bucket or route to see the real
  signal. Don't drop lead_time as a feature — the slope is probably
  masked by the bimodality, not absent.


3. Side-by-side histograms (lead_time, price)
---------------------------------------------
- lead_time histogram: heavy mass at 0-25 days, geometric decay
  outward. Bumpy plateaus at 50 and 100 days are likely month-boundary
  artifacts from querying by month.
- Reflects the cache, not booking behavior: TravelPayouts caches what
  people actually search, and most searches are weeks-to-months out.
- Modeling implication: model predictions for lead_time > 100 days are
  based on much sparser data — confidence interval should reflect this
  if the eventual app surfaces predictions for distant dates.


4. sns.histplot price by is_international  --  Stacked histogram
----------------------------------------------------------------
- The $800-900 hump is entirely international (orange). Bimodality
  hypothesis confirmed for the right side.
- BUT the left peak ($200-500) is NOT cleanly domestic — substantial
  orange chunk hiding inside it. is_international does not split the
  two modes alone.
- The low-price international cluster is short cross-border routes:
  YYZ-JFK/EWR/BOS, LAX-MEX, MIA-CUN, HND-ICN, etc. Different country,
  but short distance, so they price like domestic.
- Modeling implication: is_international is a coarse proxy that
  correlates with distance for most routes but fails on short
  cross-border hops. Distance is the real driver — is_international is
  redundant once distance is in the model, but cheap to keep as a
  binary backup signal.


5. sns.scatterplot price vs distance_km  --  Price vs distance
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Clear positive trend, as expected. Prices rise with distance. The
  cleanest single-variable relationship found so far.
- Three visible distance clusters:
    0-4500 km: dense, prices $100-700 (NA-NA backbone + cross-border)
    4500-8000 km: sparser, prices $500-1500 (trans-Atlantic territory)
    8000-14000+ km: $700-2000 (long-haul intercontinental)
- Visible GAP in route density around 4500-5500 km. The route mix has
  lots of short flights and lots of long flights, but few in between.
  Reflects geography more than anything else — there isn't much that
  falls in that distance band from NA hubs.
- Wide vertical spread at every distance — distance alone doesn't fully
  explain price. Airline, lead time, season, demand still in play.
- Relationship looks roughly linear or slightly sublinear, not
  exponential. A 14,000 km flight isn't 14× more expensive than a
  1,000 km one — closer to 4-5×. Air travel has economies of scale
  (per-km cost decreases with distance).
- Modeling implication: distance_km will be one of the most important
  features. Tree models will pick up the sublinear shape automatically;
  if I ever use a linear model, consider log-transforming distance or
  adding distance-bucket categoricals.


6. 2x2 scatter price vs lead_time by distance_bucket
----------------------------------------------------
- Top-left "All": green (long) sits high, blue (short) sits low,
  orange (medium) in between. Vertical color banding is more visible
  than any horizontal trend — distance dominates the picture.
- Short bucket: dense band, prices flat across the lead time range.
  No clear slope. If anything the upper tail (premium fares) leans
  slightly higher at low lead times, but the typical price is flat.
- Medium bucket: sparse cloud (underpopulated distance band — the
  4500-6000 km gap). Possible mild upward bump at very low lead times
  but data is too thin to trust visually.
- Long bucket: most vertical spread, prices $500-2400. No clear
  price-vs-lead-time slope visible. Data thins out past 100 days.

- Volume concentration at low lead times is real but has two stacked
  causes: (a) TravelPayouts cache density — people search close to
  departure more than far out, reflects search activity not booking
  behavior, applies to every bucket; (b) route-mix artifact — 129/230
  routes are short-haul, so the short bucket gets more rows in absolute
  terms regardless of any user behavior.
- Long flights show wider price spread than short within any lead-time
  slice. Structural reasons: more cabin/fare-class variation on
  long-haul, more airline diversity competing on intercontinental
  routes, more diverse demand mix (vacation / business / family /
  immigration) each pricing differently. Not a behavioral effect.

- I initially thought I could see a decreasing-price-with-lead-time
  trend in the long bucket, weaker in medium, near-absent in short.
  Pushed back on this — with this much scatter, the eye over-reads
  patterns. The visual "trend" is plausibly a density artifact:
  dense low-lead-time clouds appear higher because there's more data
  there, not because the typical price is higher.
- Built a median-line plot to test it. Plot 7 below covers the result.

- Modeling implication: don't drop lead_time as a feature, but lower
  expectations of how important it'll turn out to be. May end up as a
  weak signal that mainly matters for the upper price tail or in
  combination with other features (airline, day_of_week, demand).


7. Median price per 10-day lead_time bin, by distance bucket (line plot)
------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Long bucket: shows a faint but real downward slope as lead_time
  increases. The "book early = cheaper" effect is weakly present for
  intercontinental flights. Not a dramatic effect but it's there
  consistently across most of the lead_time range.
- Medium bucket: no clear correlation. Line is roughly flat with
  noise. Visual "trend" from the scatter was an illusion.
- Short bucket: no clear correlation across most of the range, but
  prices spike dramatically at ~200 days. Almost certainly outliers
  / very low data volume in those far-out bins for short routes —
  the cache is thin out there and a few high-price rows can move the
  median sharply. Don't read this as a real "buy short flights early"
  signal.

- Conclusion: lead_time has predictive value for long-haul, not for
  short or medium. The visual trend I thought I was seeing in short
  and medium scatters was indeed a density artifact, confirmed by the
  flat median lines.
- Modeling implication: tree models will pick up the long-haul
  lead_time signal automatically through interactions with
  distance_km. If using linear models, a lead_time × distance
  interaction term would be needed to capture this effect.


8. sns.boxplot price by airline_type (lcc / hybrid / legacy)
------------------------------------------------------------
- LCC box sits clearly below the others: median ~$280, IQR
  $220-$400, whisker max ~$600.
- Hybrid and legacy boxes look almost identical: both have median
  ~$400, similar IQR, similar long upper tails. The visual
  distinction is barely there.
- All three categories have heavy right tails (long-haul rows in
  each).
- Conclusion: the meaningful split is LCC vs not-LCC. The
  hybrid/legacy distinction adds very little.
- Modeling implication: could simplify type to a binary `is_lcc`
  feature without losing much signal. Tree models will figure this
  out automatically; for linear models the binary version is easier
  to reason about.


9. sns.scatterplot price vs distance, colored by airline_type
-------------------------------------------------------------
- At short distances (0-4000 km): clear color stratification, blue
  (LCC) below orange/green (hybrid/legacy).
- At medium-to-long distances (4000+ km): blue dots almost
  disappear. LCCs don't operate transatlantic / transpacific routes
  at any meaningful volume.
- The "color separation collapses at long distance" hypothesis from
  earlier doesn't quite hold the way expected — separation doesn't
  collapse, LCCs are simply absent. Hybrid and legacy overlap
  heavily at every distance.
- Modeling implication: the airline_type × distance interaction
  exists but it's mostly "LCCs are missing on long routes" rather
  than "type matters more on short routes." Tree models will pick
  this up through the joint feature; linear models would need
  explicit interaction terms.


10. sns.boxplot price by individual airline (top 15), colored by type
---------------------------------------------------------------------
- Within-type variance is enormous, exposing that type is partially
  proxying for route mix:
    Legacy:  SC ~$300 ... AA ~$370 ... AC ~$700 ... CX ~$1300
    Hybrid:  B6 ~$290 ... PD ~$300 ... WS ~$450 ... FI ~$770 ... DE ~$900
    LCC:     F9 ~$280 ... F8 ~$330 ... MM ~$370
- B6 (JetBlue, hybrid) behaves more like LCC than like its type peers.
- CX (Cathay) sits at the top of legacy because it flies long-haul, not
  because it prices premium relative to other long-haul carriers.
- LCCs are the most internally consistent: F9, F8, MM all cluster in
  the $280-$370 range.
- Modeling implication: airline itself needs to be a feature, not just
  airline_type. The within-type variance is bigger than the
  between-type variance for hybrid and legacy. Tree models handle this
  natively via the airline feature; for linear models, one-hot
  encoding or target encoding on airline is required. airline_type
  remains useful as a coarse feature but isn't sufficient alone.


11. sns.boxplot price by day_of_week
------------------------------------
- Median prices cluster Mon $405, Tue $360, Wed $370, Thu $370,
  Fri $360, Sat $370, Sun $400. Spread is modest — ~12% top to bottom.
- Mon and Sun have the highest medians AND the fattest upper tails.
  Tue-Fri cluster as the "cheap" days.
- The "Friday is significantly cheap" first impression was wrong at
  the median level — Friday's median is identical to Tue/Wed/Thu. What
  IS different about Friday is its compressed upper tail (whisker max
  ~$1170 vs $1400-1665 for other days). Fewer expensive flights leave
  on Fridays.
- Modeling implication: real signal but modest. Keep day_of_week as a
  feature. Probably ranks mid-pack in importance.


12. sns.boxplot price by transfers (0 / 1 / 2+)
-----------------------------------------------
- Strong gradient: 0 transfers $280 median, 1 transfer $520,
  2+ transfers $980.
- BUT this is heavily confounded with distance — direct flights are
  mostly short routes, multi-stop flights are mostly long routes. See
  stratified version below.


13. Price vs trip_duration_days (scatter + binned boxplot)
----------------------------------------------------------
- Scatter shows broad cloud with no obvious single-variable
  relationship. Bucketed view reveals a clear monotonic trend:
  0-3 days $300, 4-7 $370, 8-14 $510, 15+ $780.
- Again confounded with route type — long trips are mostly
  international vacations, short trips mostly domestic. See stratified
  version below.


14. Transfers × distance_bucket (1x3 panels)
--------------------------------------------
- Direct premium is REAL at every distance, not just a distance proxy.
- Short: 0 transfers $270 / 1 $300 / 2+ $480. The 2+ jump is dramatic
  (probably weird routing on thin routes); 0 vs 1 gap is small.
- Medium: 0 $390 / 1 $460 / 2+ $440. 1 vs 2+ basically tied — once
  you've added one connection, second adds little.
- Long: 0 $830 / 1 $1070 / 2+ $1200. Cleanest direct premium pattern.
- Modeling implication: transfers adds independent signal beyond
  distance. Keep as a feature. Tree models will capture the
  per-distance variation automatically.


15. Trip duration × distance_bucket (1x3 panels)
------------------------------------------------
- Within short distance: essentially FLAT ($255-$280 across all
  duration buckets). 15+ is slightly cheaper than 0-3, counterintuitive
  — possibly cheaper extended-stay routing where same-day return isn't
  needed.
- Within medium: mild upward trend ($400 → $540, ~35%).
- Within long: mild upward trend ($930 → $1080, ~16%).
- Trip duration was MOSTLY a distance proxy. Real within-route signal
  exists for medium and long but it's small.
- Modeling implication: keep trip_duration_days but expect low
  importance. Probably ranks below distance, airline, lead_time.


16. Day of week × distance_bucket (1x3 panels)
----------------------------------------------
- Most interesting finding of the stratified set. Day-of-week pattern
  PERSISTS at every distance, but the SHAPE changes by distance:
    Short: U-curve. Wed cheapest ($255), Mon/Fri/Sun highest ($290-
       $295). Business-traveler pattern (Mon-out / Fri-back / Sun
       repositioning).
    Medium: relatively flat. Mon slightly higher ($465). Others
       cluster $420-$435.
    Long: monotonic rise toward Sunday. Tue cheapest ($985), Sun
       highest ($1140). Vacation-departure pattern.
- Two different demand structures embedded in the same column: short
  routes serve business commuters, long routes serve vacationers.
- Modeling implication: day_of_week is more important than I expected.
  Interaction with distance / is_international matters — the day-of-
  week shape differs by route type. Tree models will pick this up
  automatically; linear models need an interaction term.


17. Transfers × is_international (1x2 panels)
---------------------------------------------
- Direct-flight premium exists in both groups, but magnitude differs
  dramatically.
- Domestic: 0 transfers $280 / 1 $330 / 2+ $405. ~$125 spread, ~45%
  increase top to bottom.
- International: 0 transfers $375 / 1 $830 / 2+ $1060. ~$685 spread,
  ~180% increase.
- The international direct premium is operationally explainable —
  long-haul direct flights require special aircraft and prime slots,
  so they command real premiums. Domestic connections add some cost
  but not as dramatically.
- Confirms transfers is NOT purely a distance proxy. Independent
  signal exists in both groups.
- Note: international 0-transfers median ($375) is much lower than
  the long-distance bucket's 0-transfers median ($830) from plot 14,
  because is_international includes short cross-border routes
  (YYZ-JFK etc) that are cheap even when international.


18. Day of Week × is_international (1x2 panels)
-----------------------------------------------
- Domestic: nearly FLAT. Medians range $280-$305 (~9% spread).
  Mild Fri/Sun lift but no clear weekly pattern.
- International: clear Sun premium. Medians range $625-$770 (~23%
  spread). Sun is the most expensive departure day; Fri and Tue are
  the cheapest.
- Pattern is consistent with vacation-departure timing for
  international flights: travelers leave on Sun to maximize PTO. No
  similar pattern for domestic travel.

- REVISION to earlier claim in plot 16: I called the day-of-week effect
  on short-haul a "business pattern" (Mon/Fri/Sun expensive,
  midweek cheap). Looking at the cleaner pure-domestic cut here,
  domestic travel is much flatter than that — the U-curve I saw on
  short-distance was driven by the short cross-border international
  subset (YYZ-JFK etc), not pure domestic business travel. The
  underlying mechanism is "international flights have vacation-driven
  weekly patterns; domestic is mostly flat" rather than two distinct
  business/vacation regimes.

- Modeling implication: day_of_week matters mainly for international
  flights. Domestic feature value is weak. A day_of_week ×
  is_international interaction (or equivalently, tree splits on
  is_international after splitting on day_of_week) will capture this.
